just coming up for air on holiday times here. don’t have a lot of time left to recap ‘22, but I’ll sneak in a couple posts here. let’s start w something that really pertains to next year : helping @actualbenfolds make an album! he’ll drop it sometime in ‘23. look to him for that info! but for our part, this was a real career experience, one that will continue to impact us moving forward. the whole shbang taught us SO much about our own craft. Ben is a rare, special kind of artist, and we cherished the opportunity to study under a master and friend like him. lots more to announce next year about this…

it was a privilege this year to drop another record, Juniors. like the video we made for the single (scroll for bts!), this album was an experiment in discomfort. reconning with new homes, new lives, and a changed world as SO MANY factors left their marks, it’s as raw and heartfelt as we’ve yet delved. it continues to mean the world each and every time we hear from you, as you connect and vibe along w/ it!
🎥 @benjaminmlieber

we just dropped a cover of @blink182 "Dammit." it's a song that was long ago near-and-dear to us, refurbished this year for our 1997 shows. thematically, it feels right for NYE. the shock and horror baked into that line "well, i guess this is growing up." I feel that way a little every NYE. this ain't how I saw it going, but boy it's going! 
​

Happy new year, friends! see you in 2023!
@tomdelonge @markhoppus @travisbarker

gearing up for some duo shows in the coming weeks first at @folk_alliance and then on the w coast opening for the amazing @thelonebellow (tix in bio!). this ol’ here song is about a struggle to find one’s purpose. realizing that our physical bodies - meek, weak, and kinda blind - certainly wouldn’t have cut it in the days of the cavemen, but still, hopefully, we have a humble role to play here in ‘23. for us, getting out on the road is always so very re-centering. it’s the place we can plainly see what a gift it is to do this work. can’t wait. 

“I sure don’t have eyes like an eagle’s
I couldn’t be waiting for war
Why should I think that I’d have survived
In the days of yore
But the gifts of the Greeks oh they taught me
Radio favors the bold
The key to survival is pleasing your rivals
Till the days unfold
As the hour grows
As the hour grows
I know that I can keep the voice of doubt from speaking on its own
Cuz I’ve always been a silent figure
And I’ve never been a man of stone”
2 weeks out here we go!

couple weeks back we went into a studio in Western, MA with some friends thinking we'd low-stakes capture a few new ideas and sounds. we finished 13 songs in 10 days, and now we have a surprising new piece of intel to grapple with : shit, we just made an album! 

so, while we chew on that, here's what we can say now : we have new songs to play, and a new tour to play them on! this summer we'll be out opening for and playing in the band of Ben Folds as he supports the release of his beautiful new album "What Matters Most." We spent several weeks in Nashville last summer helping Ben make this LP, it was a rare honor to work with and learn from a true master of the craft. We honestly can’t wait, this is going to be special! 

… and we already talking about burning some mix tape style self-leaked cds of some new songs, so I can almost promise you we’ll have something new (and appropriately bootleg) to share out there. 
@actualbenfolds
starting with the basics. #pride #pridemonth #boydad

file this one under : "things we never thought we'd do." just over a year ago, @actualbenfolds called and asked if we'd fly to Nashville for a month to help him make an album, his first in many years. so we did. and it's out today... "What Matters Most."
 
the experience changed our lives. certainly, first and foremost, to be able to interact with a master not just in the studio, but leading up to it for a period that we called "emotional preproduction." then to sit there in the studio and watch him work : focused solely on getting it there and bound by nothing else. And then to participate in the waiting as a fan as he finished it up. To listen fresh and appreciate the WHOLE thing anew.
 
what we learned from Ben, and what Ben helped us see in ourselves, has already had tremendous impact on our creative flow and output. More on that another day, but for now, go scope this beautiful album from folds right the f now.

nothing beats local music festivals and playing with friends. we’ll be heading to @collectionband new hometown Soil & Sky Fest. it’ll be fun to be back with such an incredible band. NC peeps please come for some great vibes and hangs. <3

t O u R - we are out here to help celebrate in the release of @actualbenfolds new album, What Matters Most. so I guess it’s appropriate that we would so quickly fall deeply back in touch with these things that matter so much to us : friendship, togetherness, realism, harmony, and song. Thanks, friends, new and old who’ve joined us out here for these special moments.

tim here. if you know me well, you know I geek out about songs. not as entertainment, but as architecture. I’ve spent years evaluating what’s inside them, how they’re made, and why they sometimes stand so long and strong and tall. there are a few songs I‘ve poured over endlessly with anyone who will listen. @reginaspektor wrote a few of them. we got to sing and hang with her at @beacontheatre, and harmonizing w her was a career highlight. here’s a vid of us singing together on the Ben Folds song “You Don’t Know Me.” 

Tangentially, here’s a friggin essay I just wrote for fun on Regina’s song “Sampson” (NOT in vid). This is for me, I love this shit.

“Sampson” is not *exactly* about the Bible story Sampson and Delilah. It participates in the story tho, allowing the Bible plot we already know to accentuate the tragedy of *this* story that Regina tells. It’s actually about Sampson’s lover BEFORE he met Delilah, the one he perhaps left FOR Delilah. And Sampson broke her heart: “You are my sweetest downfall, I loved you first.” Their love was simple and intense, and she was great for him. In fact, she could even cut his hair without robbing him of his power. “I cut his hair myself one night a pair of dull scissors in the yellow light, and he told me that I’d done alright and he kissed me till the morning light.” That’s pretty remarkable and romantic, since we know that Sampson’s eventual downfall comes when Delilah cuts his hair. This first love has been forgotten though “the history books forgot about us, and a bible didn’t mention us,” because all we remember is the colossal downfall that Sampson stumbles into next. 

But doesn’t it break your heart all the more to know that Sampson shouldn’t have left this first love behind? The protagonist of the song loved him first but she had to suffer her own downfall because of Sampson’s folly. It hurts because you’re like “Sampson, dude! This is the one! Don’t lose her!” But he does, and boy does he pay the price! The tragedy is that they’re both ruined. every time I listen, I’m always rooting for a different outcome: that Sampson might make the right call and stay with Regina’s character. he never does. What a song.

can we play your backyard? we're serious! 

We're releasing a new album next year and want to learn more about these songs. We can't think of a better setting than an intimate evening under the stars among friends. Which is why we'll be embarking on a week-long backyard tour this September.

It'll be the two of us, a small PA, our van, and a small group of fans each night. We'll play some unreleased songs for our upcoming album, as well as some of your old favorites.
​
First things first, we need hosts!

Do you live near one of the cities in the image and have the perfect backyard or outdoor space that can hold 25-100 people? If you said "yes," please snap some photos of your space, fill out our questionnaire (link in bio) and we'll be in touch next week.

TIX IN BIO! we’ve spent most of this year opening shows for other artists in beautiful venues all over the place. while that's all well & good (amazing, actually), things around here have been feeling way too "normal" to us lately. So let's shake it up a little with a limited run of backyard shows!

backyard tours were a pandemic discovery that, honestly, saved our butts. we're doing it again, but not because it's covid-safe. what’s the opposite of socially distant?? socially together... yeah, that's it!!! such special nights, amazing opportunities to get to 
know y'all and share more and differently. 

we also just cut a whole record of songs, so we want to put some road miles on them with you!

here’s some of our new song “Apple Tree” in a venue stairwell. we been playing it out on the road every night on tour… have you heard it? this song means a lot to us. it’s about the ugly, confusing, randomly firing beauty of life. we can’t wait to share it as a single!!

touring feels different than it used to. before the pandemic, it was a thing we did. now it’s a thing we *get to do*. every tour feels precious and fleeting. how do we better appreciate a moment? serious question actually… y’all got any tricks?

one of our favorite shows of the tour happened yesterday morning at an elementary school in Oakland, CA. what a pleasure it was to share songs and stories with this awesome and thoughtful group of kiddos! thanks to the @bayareamusicproject for facilitating the opportunity! as dads ourselves, inspiring youngsters with music and, WAY more importantly, self expression is so near and dear to our hearts. lucky us.

what I love and remember best about backyard touring is the Beautiful Unexpected™ each and every night. one evening, that ol’ fickle New England weather forced us to cancel the show VERY last minute. we sent the cancelation email about 90 min before showtime. most got the memo, but still about 50 showed up. it had just started raining and our hosts, the Clewleys (cutest family on earth), started actively welcoming these strangers. so we set up on their front step and played an unplugged set as the rain softly fell. can’t wait to see what’s in store next month back out there in fans’ backyards. the people, the places, the moments, all so wonderfully distinct. backyard schedule and tix at link in bio. 

#backyard #acoustic #unplugged #autumn

tim here. my first memory of my best pal paul is from 1st grade in Sturbridge, MA. my elementary school class was joining up for a day with a class of “big kid” 5th graders. My older brother, Ryan, was in that class. I remember my friends and I flocking to him because #status. as we gathered ‘round Ry, a tiny, dark haired, thick glasses, large toothed classmate of his said in a voice not dissimilar from the Toy Story “the claw” worshippers, “Ryan, you have many followers!” I looked at young Paul Wright and did not think “I will spend my life making music with this boy.” But it’s the first time he appeared on my life radar. it was a great start.

tim here. I’m keeping a journal of special and affirming moments on this run of shows. it was my therapist’s idea, and last night’s backyard outside of Buffalo gave me a full page to write out. gosh, what beats the convergence of music and family and spontaneously firing self expression from ALL angles?? it was beautiful, thank you for that. now off to fix an f’d up guitar before Pittsburgh tonight.

Paul here. As I walked out the door for tour my wife Liz said “go fill up on your fans”. I appreciated it but I couldn’t fully conjure that feeling that comes with sharing evenings with you all. It’s so different from the equally amazing but less personal exchange of the theater tours we’ve been doing with Folds this summer. Sharing new songs, resurrecting old ones and the stories that inspired them, getting a glimpse into y’all’s lives from post show chats where there’s no bouncer trying to move people out of the venue. It’s the fill up I didn’t know I needed. Thank you.

Happy 100,000 to our beloved van, The Spirit of Beverly. I kno we didn’t win a Grammy or nothin, but a few shouts to a few friends who helped get this van here. after getting off stage playing Ben Folds songs w Ben Folds, we’ve realized there’s great fun and joy to be had running out to our busking roots outside of the venue! @actualbenfolds

so we played London’s esteemed Royal Albert Hall last night. the hardest part about playing a big famous venue in a big famous city is that so often the hype and anticipation can manifest in a nervous energy within and around us that tinges a whole experience. shows like this *can* devolve into an exercise in survival and little more. Not last night. Last night was magic in the face of pomp and circumstance. THANK YOU to Ben Folds for always setting the bar so high, for divining greatness out of those around him, and for the opportunity to unplug and fuckin rip a song we made up in this cavernous acoustical chamber built to resonate the voices of far greater men and women than little old us. Humbled and heartened. So much love. 

@royalalberthall @actualbenfolds @mandy_plays_bass @pauldumasdrums @ross_garren @blakeismyname

tonight, our last of the album release shows with @actualbenfolds in Edinburgh, is fixin to be an emotional one. to have started this journey back in ‘17 that lead to making an album with an all-time great and hero… and to have toured it with him all over the friggin place… boy, how lucky are we? Whatever comes next, it’s been a joy of joys to wake up for so much of ‘23 to dig a little deeper into “What Matters Most.” Oh! And just a few tix left for our Monday (20 Nov) London headline at @thelexingtonlondon. #whatmattersmost #benfolds

we’ll be playing our LAST headline of 2023 tomorrow in London at @thelexingtonlondon followed by an extended break into ‘24 because… PAUL AND LIZ ARE HAVING A BABY GIRL IN JANUARY!! And to sprinkle even more joy, today’s his bday too! Say congrats, say hbd, say f**k off, as you wish! help us have our first EVER overseas sold out show to celebrate. Joy and love on the horizon! And new music in a new year, mark my words!

Hello from the airplane home! Here’s a gratitude gush about this UK tour, followed by some chit chat in the comments, followed by turning these phones off for a few days to focus on our boys and families. Simply put, this tour made us feel the luckiest. We weren’t sure what to expect out there, since we were traveling exclusively as “Ben Folds’ band,” and not as his opening act like we usually do. We added a show in London, our first overseas headline since 2019, honestly just to do SOMETHING directly in service of our own band. we had low expectations. 

It didn’t take long though for us to hear the ancient cobblestone streets calling us back to our busking roots. A day or 2 after locking into some daily street performing, Ben generously invited/challenged us to start playing a song of ours completely unplugged in these sometimes massive, cavernous acoustical spaces. The whole while we were exploring the most incredible towns with what has become a very tight knit touring family… my goodness. Yes, lucky. there’s a quote etched in metal that I super glued to my guitar case: “luck is when opportunity bumps into preparation.” The joy of this tour really felt like years in the making. Thanks to Ben Folds and all of you for these incredible opportunities! The cherry on top of the whole sundae definitely was selling out that lone tall heights show. Friends new and old say hello in the comments, each and every one of you mean the world to us.

#spotifywrapped has felt uncomfortable to us since it started… much like the holidays in general, it has this way of blending lofty intention with unhealthy execution. SO we had an idea as to how we can more purely focus on what we LOVE about it : acknowledging YOU, our people! let’s have a digital pizza party! If you are a .01% top listener on Spotify, dm us that screen shot and stand by for info!

jenny ghost grabbed this tender snuggly moment last night, so I thought I’d share… this whole holiday ramp up thing is such a different and lovely experience w these little people to filter it all through. grateful for moments like this.
don’t bring porn for copping… to a daycare or to anywhere else, ok?

years back we got together in our buddy’s basement (@roccoderosamusic ) and covered @jonimitchell and @persistentproductions came and filmed it. I still love this performance, and these haircuts. #merrywhatever
we should be able to watch a *little* porn at Christmas parties. #christmas #letitsnow #fail

now THIS is our way of doing #spotifywrapped… we invited the top .01% of our listeners (as generated by @spotify year-end graphics) to have a pizza party on Google Meet. we ate pizza, laughed, cried, shared… it was simply delightful. *this* is what those disembodied numbers on those homogenous graphics mean to us. it’s about the connection, the cave diving with fellow cave divers. and the .01% thing was arbitrary to keep it small… to ALL of you who spent even 5 minutes w/ us in ‘23 digging deeper on streaming platforms, in a venue, in a backyard, on a street corner, on a mountain, or in a livestream… truly thank you. more in ‘24!!
-tim and paul

not at all into year-end lists, but this was such a special moment of ‘23. thank you @royalalberthall for these acoustics. thank you, Ben Folds @actualbenfolds for entrusting us with 3 minutes of unplugged stage time during a huge night for you (you kno, as you packed a world famous venue and damn near burned the place down as only you can do).
here’s to letting that shit go. Happy new years, all. New music next year. Let’s go #newyear

introducing the newest member of the TH fam, 
Laurel Rebecca Wright!

01/05/24 at 2:55pm
7 lbs 9 oz, 20.5 inches

Laurel spent her first day getting some extra oxygen in the NICU but is now joyfully reunited with us. Feeling immense gratitude for my hero Liz, the amazing medical staff who cared for us, every snowy tall heights tour that prepared me to slide us home from the hospital - and this community for welcoming our wee little Laurel ❤️
